luding turbulence. Numerical Analysis is clearly understood as part of Scientific Computing. The focus is on the efficiency of algorithms, i.e. speed, reliability, and robustness, which directly leads to the concept of adaptivity in algorithms. The theoretical derivation and analysis is kept as elementary as possible. Nevertheless required somewhat more sophisticated mathematical theory is summarized in comprehensive form in an appendix. Complex relations are explained by numerous figures and illustrating examples. Non-trivial problems from regenerative energy, nanotechnology, surgery, and physiology are inserted. The text will appeal to graduate students and researchers on the job in mathematics, science, and technology. Conceptually, it has been written as a textbook including exercises and a software list, but at the same time it should be well-suited for self-study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDifferential equations, EllipticxNumerical solutionsvTextbooks. 0aDifferential equations, EllipticxNumerical solutionsxTextbooks. 0aDifferential equations, ParabolicxNumerical solutionsvTextbooks. 0aDifferential equations, ParabolicxNumerical solutionsxTextbooks. 4aAdaptive Method. 4aDifference Method. 4aFinite Element Method. 4aNumerical Methods. 4aNumerics. 4aPDEs. 4aPartial Differential Equations. 4aScientific computing. 7aMATHEMATICS / Applied.2bisacsh  aAdaptive.  aAlgorithm.  aNumerical Solution.  aPartial Differential Equation.  aScientific Computing.1 aWeiser, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Mathematics 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023847108iTitle is part of eBoo